            detail: {
              overview: `Scaled Dot-Product Attention:
  Inputs: Q (queries), K (keys), V (values) — shape (seq_len, d_k) each
  Attention(Q, K, V) = softmax(QKᵀ / √d_k) · V

  QKᵀ: (seq_len, seq_len) similarity matrix — every pair of positions
  /√d_k: scaling to prevent softmax saturation
  softmax: attention weights — each row sums to 1
  ·V: weighted average of values

  Why √d_k?
  If q,k ~ N(0,1): qᵀk ~ N(0, d_k). Without scaling, variance grows with d_k.
  At large d_k, dot products are large → softmax saturates → near-one-hot output.
  Near-one-hot softmax = near-zero gradient (saturation kills learning).
  /√d_k normalises variance back to O(1).

Multi-Head Attention (MHA):
  Run h heads in parallel, each with smaller d_k = d_model/h:
  headᵢ = Attention(QWᵢᴼ, KWᵢᴷ, VWᵢᵛ)     Wᵢ are learned projections
  MHA(Q,K,V) = Concat(head₁,...,headₕ) · Wᴼ
  Each head attends to different positions/patterns simultaneously.

Positional Encoding:
  Self-attention is permutation-equivariant — order is ignored without PE.
  Sinusoidal (Vaswani 2017): PE[pos,2i] = sin(pos/10000^(2i/d_model))
  Learned absolute (BERT, GPT-2): nn.Embedding(max_len, d_model)
  RoPE (LLaMA, Mistral): rotary — relative positions, no max_len limit`,
